 <p><br><br><br><br><br><p align="center"><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=13354" target ="_blank"><img border="0" src="http://members.home.com/candon/Signature.jpg" width="339" height="67"></a></p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f7f7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/ugregar1.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gregar1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Dubious Poster</span><br> <font color=#778899>(1/17/02 12:57:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/finnoruukserverfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=194.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Ok, why do we care, and what is evil?</span><hr size=1> Ugle,<br>
<br>
I'm trying to follow where you're going here.  There's a lot to absorb.  Unfortunately, you force me to be a mugwump on what you contend. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   I'm not &quot;outraged&quot; by your opinion.  I'm just not sure how your outrage at people's outrage or sadness is any more relevant than theirs?  I chose to view your opinions with no anger.  I sometimes think you split your hairs a lot more microscopically than most, certainly more than I am willing to.  But, I fully respect that your personal opinions, beliefs, and feelings belong to you, and far be it from me to tell you they are &quot;wrong&quot;.  Perhaps that's the only inherent difference I have with you.<br>
<br>
Does someone have the right to feel compassion for another human being's pain, even if they didn't know them personally?  Do they have the right to be outraged at the senseless death of another human being, even if they didn't know them personally?  I'd have to say about as much right as you do to be outraged that they do.  Note, I did NOT say more.  I hesitate to judge your subjective feelings about this, your motivation to feel outrage, or even question any &quot;hidden agenda&quot; that causes your outrage.  That is where our opinions part ways.<br>
<br>
I see a car hit someone's dog on the road.  Do I feel sad for the family who lost their pet?  Well, yeah.  Do I feel the sadness as much as if it were my own dog, Sparky?  Well, no.  A co-worker's Mom dies after a long, protracted illness.  Am I saddened?  Well, yes.  My best friend's Mom dies after a long, protracted illness.  Am I saddened?  Well, yes.  Perhaps more because it is my friend's Mom?  Perhaps even more because I knew their Mom personally?  Well, yes.  My Mom dies in the same way?  A different level of sadness?  Well, yes.  Are any of the three feelings any less valid because of my varied personal involvement?  You seem to be saying yes.  Is it a further stretch to feel a differing sadness because we share a common interest?  I don't feel suitably qualified to make that kind of judgement.  Understand, I don't recall giving you the right to validate or invalidate my subjective emotions about any event.  For the same reason, I won't judge your feeling about other's feelings.<br>
<br>
I totally agree with you about the sadness about death.  If someone subscribes to any of the myriad religious beliefs in the world, the person who has died has moved on to another, better place.  Hell(pun intended), even the true nihilist will admit that the dead no longer exist, and can not be touched by the pain and suffering in the world we inhabit.  We don't mourn for the dead, we mourn for those who still live, for ourselves.  You can argue that this is entirely selfish, IMHO it is.  I can't go so far as to say it's wrong.  For most of us mere mortals, death is the big meany at the end of the line.  There, but for the grace of God, go I?  Is this a bad thing?  Are we all evil, because this is true?  I don't think I am qualified to make that judgement, simply because I am mortal.  Yes, Ugle, somewhere in our heart of hearts, we are all saying &quot;I'm really glad it isn't me&quot;.  Your point?<br>
<br>
